<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>emsenn.net</title><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/</link><description>Recent content on emsenn.net</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Mon, 02 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Kan Extension</title><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/kan-extension/</link><pubDate>Mon, 02 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/kan-extension/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;A Kan extension is the universal way to extend a &lt;a href="./functor.md" class="link-internal"&gt;functor&lt;/a&gt; along another &lt;a href="./functor.md" class="link-internal"&gt;functor&lt;/a&gt;. Given &lt;a href="./functor.md" class="link-internal"&gt;functors&lt;/a&gt; F: C → D and K: C → E, the left Kan extension Lan_K(F): E → D is the &amp;ldquo;best approximation&amp;rdquo; of F that factors through K.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The left Kan extension Lan_K(F) is characterized by a &lt;a href="./natural-transformation.md" class="link-internal"&gt;natural transformation&lt;/a&gt; η: F ⇒ Lan_K(F) ∘ K that is universal: for any other &lt;a href="./functor.md" class="link-internal"&gt;functor&lt;/a&gt; G: E → D with a &lt;a href="./natural-transformation.md" class="link-internal"&gt;natural transformation&lt;/a&gt; F ⇒ G ∘ K, there is a unique &lt;a href="./natural-transformation.md" class="link-internal"&gt;natural transformation&lt;/a&gt; Lan_K(F) ⇒ G making everything commute. The right Kan extension Ran_K(F) satisfies the dual universal &lt;a href="../../../../../sociology/terms/property.md" class="link-internal"&gt;property&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title/><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/category/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/category/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;A category C consists of a collection of &lt;a href="./object.md" class="link-internal"&gt;objects&lt;/a&gt;, a collection of &lt;a href="./morphism.md" class="link-internal"&gt;morphisms&lt;/a&gt; between objects, and a &lt;a href="./composition.md" class="link-internal"&gt;composition&lt;/a&gt; operation satisfying two laws.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For every pair of objects A and B, there is a collection Hom(A, B) of morphisms from A to B. For every composable pair &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;B&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;f : A \to B&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;g&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;B&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;C&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;g : B \to C&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, there is a composite &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;g&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∘&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;C&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;g \circ f : A \to C&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. For every object A, there is an &lt;a href="./identity-morphism.md" class="link-internal"&gt;identity morphism&lt;/a&gt; &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;i&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;d&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;\mathrm{id}_A : A \to A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. These satisfy:&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title/><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/functor/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/functor/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;A functor &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;F&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;C&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;D&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;F : C \to D&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is a map from one &lt;a href="./category.md" class="link-internal"&gt;category&lt;/a&gt; to another that preserves the structure. It sends &lt;a href="./object.md" class="link-internal"&gt;objects&lt;/a&gt; to objects and &lt;a href="./morphism.md" class="link-internal"&gt;morphisms&lt;/a&gt; to morphisms. It does not break &lt;a href="./composition.md" class="link-internal"&gt;composition&lt;/a&gt; or identities: if &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;f&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;g&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;g&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; compose to &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;h&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;h&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; in C, then &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;F&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;F(f)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;F&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;g&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;F(g)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; compose to &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;F&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;h&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;F(h)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; in D. If &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;i&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;d&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;\mathrm{id}_A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is an &lt;a href="./identity-morphism.md" class="link-internal"&gt;identity morphism&lt;/a&gt;, then &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;F&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;i&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;d&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;i&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;d&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;F&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;F(\mathrm{id}_A) = \mathrm{id}_{F(A)}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;That is the whole definition. A functor maps things and arrows between things, and it respects how arrows chain together. A functor is to categories what a homomorphism is to groups or a continuous map is to topological spaces — a structure-preserving translation between structured worlds.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title/><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/identity-morphism/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/identity-morphism/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;The identity morphism &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;i&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;d&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;\mathrm{id}_A : A \to A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is the &lt;a href="./morphism.md" class="link-internal"&gt;morphism&lt;/a&gt; on an &lt;a href="./object.md" class="link-internal"&gt;object&lt;/a&gt; A that acts as the neutral element for &lt;a href="./composition.md" class="link-internal"&gt;composition&lt;/a&gt;. Composing with the identity before or after any morphism leaves it unchanged:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∘&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;i&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;d&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mspace width="2em"/&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;i&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;d&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;B&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∘&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;f \circ \mathrm{id}_A = f \qquad \mathrm{id}_B \circ f = f&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;p&gt;for every morphism &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;B&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;f : A \to B&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Every &lt;a href="./category.md" class="link-internal"&gt;category&lt;/a&gt; is required to have an identity morphism for every object. This is one of the two axioms of a category, alongside associativity of composition. Without identity morphisms, there would be no notion of &amp;ldquo;doing nothing&amp;rdquo; — no baseline against which other morphisms can be measured. The identity morphism is to composition what zero is to addition or one is to multiplication.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title/><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/isomorphism/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/isomorphism/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;An isomorphism is a &lt;a href="./morphism.md" class="link-internal"&gt;morphism&lt;/a&gt; &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;B&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;f : A \to B&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; that has a two-sided inverse: a morphism &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;g&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;B&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;g : B \to A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; such that &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;g&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∘&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;i&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;d&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;g \circ f = \mathrm{id}_A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∘&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;g&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;i&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant="normal"&gt;d&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;B&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;f \circ g = \mathrm{id}_B&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. You can go there and come back and end up where you started, in both directions.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Two &lt;a href="./object.md" class="link-internal"&gt;objects&lt;/a&gt; connected by an isomorphism are isomorphic. They are structurally identical from the perspective of the &lt;a href="./category.md" class="link-internal"&gt;category&lt;/a&gt;. Every property expressible in categorical terms is preserved by isomorphism. This makes isomorphism the correct notion of &amp;ldquo;sameness&amp;rdquo; in category theory: not literal equality of objects, but the existence of a structure-preserving correspondence that can be undone.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title/><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/natural-transformation/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/natural-transformation/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;A natural transformation &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;α&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;F&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⇒&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;G&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;\alpha : F \Rightarrow G&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; between two &lt;a href="./functor.md" class="link-internal"&gt;functors&lt;/a&gt; &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;F&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator="true"&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;G&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;C&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;D&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;F, G : C \to D&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; assigns to each &lt;a href="./object.md" class="link-internal"&gt;object&lt;/a&gt; c in C a &lt;a href="./morphism.md" class="link-internal"&gt;morphism&lt;/a&gt; &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;α&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;F&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;G&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;\alpha_c : F(c) \to G(c)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; in D, such that for every morphism &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msup&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em"&gt;′&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/msup&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;f : c \to c&amp;#x27;&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; in C, the following square commutes:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;G&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∘&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;α&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;α&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;msup&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em"&gt;′&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/msup&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∘&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;F&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;G(f) \circ \alpha_c = \alpha_{c&amp;#x27;} \circ F(f)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;p&gt;The commutativity condition is the substance of &amp;ldquo;natural.&amp;rdquo; It says that &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;α&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;\alpha&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; does not depend on arbitrary choices. Transforming an object and then mapping it forward gives the same result as mapping it forward and then transforming it. The components &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;α&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;\alpha_c&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; are coherent across the entire category — they fit together into a single, globally consistent mapping from F to G.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title/><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/object/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/object/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;An object is one of the two kinds of data in a &lt;a href="./category.md" class="link-internal"&gt;category&lt;/a&gt; — the things that &lt;a href="./morphism.md" class="link-internal"&gt;morphisms&lt;/a&gt; go between.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What counts as an object depends on the category. In Set, objects are &lt;a href="../../sets/terms/set.md" class="link-internal"&gt;sets&lt;/a&gt;. In Top, objects are topological spaces. In a group G viewed as a one-object category, there is exactly one object (the group itself), and morphisms are the group elements. In a &lt;a href="../../posets/terms/partial-order.md" class="link-internal"&gt;partial order&lt;/a&gt; viewed as a thin category, each element of the poset is an object.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Commutative Diagram</title><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/commutative-diagram/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/commutative-diagram/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;A commutative diagram is a diagram of &lt;a href="./object.md" class="link-internal"&gt;objects&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="./morphism.md" class="link-internal"&gt;morphisms&lt;/a&gt; in which all directed paths between the same two objects compose to the same &lt;a href="./morphism.md" class="link-internal"&gt;morphism&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If a diagram contains two paths from A to C — say f: A → B followed by g: B → C, and also h: A → C directly — then the diagram commutes when g ∘ f = h. The visual layout encodes an equation: any two routes through the diagram that start and end at the same objects must give the same composite.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Composition</title><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/composition/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/composition/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;Composition is the operation that combines two consecutive &lt;a href="./morphism.md" class="link-internal"&gt;morphisms&lt;/a&gt; into one. If f goes from A to B and g goes from B to C, their composite g ∘ f goes from A to C. You do f first, then g. The notation reads right to left: g ∘ f means &amp;ldquo;g after f.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Composition must follow two rules. First, associativity: if you have three morphisms in a row, it does not matter which pair you compose first. h ∘ (g ∘ f) = (h ∘ g) ∘ f. Second, the unit law: every &lt;a href="./object.md" class="link-internal"&gt;object&lt;/a&gt; has an &lt;a href="./identity-morphism.md" class="link-internal"&gt;identity morphism&lt;/a&gt; that does nothing when composed with other morphisms. f ∘ id = f, and id ∘ g = g.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Morphism</title><link>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/morphism/</link><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://emsenn.net/library/math/domains/categories/domains/ordinary-categories/terms/morphism/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;A morphism is a directed connection from one &lt;a href="./object.md" class="link-internal"&gt;object&lt;/a&gt; to another inside a &lt;a href="./category.md" class="link-internal"&gt;category&lt;/a&gt;. It extends a plain &lt;a href="../../../../terms/directed-graph.md" class="link-internal"&gt;directed relation&lt;/a&gt; with the requirement that morphisms compose: if f goes from A to B and g goes from B to C, then there is a composite g ∘ f going from A to C, and this composition is associative.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Every morphism has a source (where it starts) and a target (where it lands). Every object has an &lt;a href="./identity-morphism.md" class="link-internal"&gt;identity morphism&lt;/a&gt; — an arrow from itself to itself that does nothing when composed with other arrows.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>